    <h3>Story</h3>
    <p>In Book 3 of Interstellar Spring, Captain Catalina Mondragon and her crew find themselves at the mercy of scoundrels armed with both ancient and futuristic weapons in a region of space not beholden to the Charter. </p>
    <p>In an effort to get to Epsilon-V and learn about the monstrous insects that killed their last Entomologist, the crew of the Artemis must pass through a region of space where violence is still used to solve problems. While there, Fin Zerog must confront a scorned lover and a pilot maybe even more skilled than herself. Farah Relkor, despite years of experience as an Interstellar Botanist, drags her husband through a field of poison ivy. Osha McKenna tries to distract herself with conspiracy theories about secret aliens before she must rescue her crush, Roman Jupiter, who falls in love with a moody, techno-genius of a princess. Captain Mondragon learns more about the mysterious disease that killed her father and is forced to grapple with what it really means to be a Captain for the Institute and a champion of the Charter. </p>
    <p>Iceoaks and Warblers starts with a meal on the organic ship, the Artemis, but by the end of this book our intrepid Interstellar Ecologists must maneuver melting permafrost, falling trees, squirrel gardeners, disgruntled old men, garish songbirds and handcrafted shotguns if they have any hope of returning to a part of the Galaxy that shows them the respect they deserve. Iceoaks and Warblers is the third book in the Interstellar Spring series, and has the same sort of ecological, humorous and sensual details that readers enjoyed in the previous installments.</p>
