        <h3>Excerpt</h3>
        <p>Mankind has always looked to the stars in hopes of finding signs of life. We found nothing. No insects, no plants, no bacteria. Nothing. A century ago, with the Earth on the verge of total environmental collapse, the Institute for Organic Expansion launched 51 Seedpods equipped with FTL Bubbledrives and loaded with eggs, seeds and spores and sent them to empty Earth-like planets to give mankind somewhere to go once Earth was used up. It worked, mostly. Now, Interstellar Ecologists stabilize these young, planetary ecosystems to strengthen mankind’s place in a lifeless galaxy. </p>
        <p>Catalina Solaris Xao Mondragon is the greatest Captain to ever serve Institute, and the first to admit she's nothing without her crew of Ecologists. When Catalina loses her Entomologist to a swarm of horrible insects evolved on one of the Seeded Worlds, she must scramble to find a replacement who can find a way to stop the monsters that ate her last one. But the only bug-guy Catalina knows who is good enough to work on the Institute’s finest Organic ship is her ex-boyfriend, and he has the infuriating habit of falling in love with a different woman on every Seeded World he visits. </p>
        <p>Roman Jupiter is her best bet to understand the monstrous bugs that killed Dr. Mercurian, and surely a few bruised feelings are worth a planet? Catalina thinks it is worth the risk, even if her crew of Interstellar Ecologists have other feelings about Jupiter and his lousy poetry. </p>
        <p>Interstellar Spring is a humorous space opera about love in all of its forms: be it for the brave people who try to do what they believe in, or the wondrous flora and fauna who really run the worlds around us.</p>
